values.QID1_TEXT: Falling in love with someone else when I was married to another person.
Not taking a timeout to spend time with the important people in my life. I have had a tendency to place work responsibilities ahead of my family and others.
Not fully appreciating and enjoying the period of life when my children were young.
Not studying abroad in college
I did not persist at university and in early adulthood with creative writing
Letting someone else take the blame for my wrongdoing
Not visiting my parents/grandparents more when they were alive.
Not taking more chances.

I regret being constantly over-committed during my working years, being too busy to spend time at home with my family and generally enjoy life and health. I think it was a way to avoid being responsible for my choices. Now that I'm retired, I'm going slower and enjoying life more, but it is hard to overcome life-long habits.
I didn't learn to speak fluently in another language
Automatically doing what I thought was expected of me, rather than considering what I actually needed to feel happy and fulfilled.
Not spending more time with my near-death mother when she was in the hospital.
Not spending enough time with my parents when I was in my 30s.
I regret not learning how to seek help sooner
I wish I had been more willing to fail; that is, I wish I had been bolder in engaging in situations where I was not likely to succeed, for the sake of learning from the experience.
I majored in Business for a secure job instead of the English I loved.
Not consistently following my heart over my mind in some career decisions.

Once, as a child, I made an innocently intended remark that I MUCH later realized must have been extremely hurtful to my Mother. I regret that I made the remark, and also that I never found a way to apologize that wouldn't have made things worse by bringing it up.
I have never studied  abroad only in Germany. I had the chance but was too shy to go for it.
I should have had therapy sooner
I didn't take my wife's mental health issues more seriously before we had children.
That I didn't go to film school.
Not quitting that job sooner
Not taking more risks earlier in life - exploring the world, meeting more people, following my heart into adventures that didn't "fit the box".

I regret not having focused my career on one rather obscure topic that I was passionate about and could become a serious expert in over 30 years such that I could feel my expertise is really valuable at the end of my career and would give me as sense of being in demand even as I pass traditional retirement age.
Not joining the military. I could have served my country more in a life of active service. I finally came to government service and love my work. I wish I'd started earlier.
I wish I had been more adventurous when I was a young adult, and been more confident - maybe traveled or studied abroad.
Believing the world lives by my standards.
Not dealing with my eating disorder sooner.
Abandoning good friends
Trying to be perfect!
Gaining weight, a few pounds a year, through my life.
Being concerned about what others think of me.
I wish I had not had a boyfriend through college who monopolized my time and I had met more great people.  I went to an amazing university!!
I did not take financial risks that would have made me more money when I could afford to take the risk (i.e., invest in real estate). I played it safe and now I am still scraping by.
Wish I would have committed to my now wife earlier. Life has been so much better since.
Not taking bold chances early enough in life
Starting saving and financial planning sooner
Focusing on work more than on people. From missing family events to avoiding work network opportunities.
Living a life for God sooner. Putting others and my goals before God’s plan for me.
I sacrificed family time for work time.
Infidelity in my relationship prior to our marriage
I havent yet published a book. I havent even written a full manuscript.
I regret that I have not honored a commitment to a friend, which led to me not having contact with him anymore.
Not being brave enough to have a child through adoption or artificial insemination.
Not being bolder - I didn't realize how much growing up poor limited what I thought was possible for myself and people like me.
That I spent much too long planning to do things instead of getting up and doing them.
As a child, how I took my frustrations out on my horse - the pain I caused my horse who I considered my best friend.

I was mean to my mom during a speech at my wedding (I was 36 when I got married.) It was totally ungracious and unwarranted, and was probably a result of exhaustion, alcohol and stress. But I felt horrible about it that night and ever since.
That I didn’t have people over more often for dinner and host more parties.
Not promoting myself more in my career.  Allowed others to take credit for my work.
I haven't travelled more
I regret not standing up for myself in the workplace — fair pay, respect, advancement opportunity.
Not picking a professional career path earlier in life, and going straight into the workforce without a college degree.
I regret that I have not been more patient in my dealings with others.
Waiting too long to move from my past employer.  I was there 20 years and should have moved on sooner.

I regret not sitting for the CPA exam right after graduation. I should have thought farther ahead and imagined my career 10 years down the road and the flexibility that the CPA credential would provide.
Believing knew everything and ignoring the wisdom of elders.
Should have been bold enough to say 'No' to things that were abusive to self.
That I wasn’t smarter about money management and investing at an earlier age.

Not telling my dad, while he was still well, how much I appreciated all the sacrifices he made for us in his life choices and his work. (I was 20 when he died, so I wasn't a fully-formed and conscientious adult yet, so I don't blame myself too badly.)
Not letting go of people who created a negative environment for me. Always trying to empathise and keep my bridges has also robbed me of confidence.
Not taking charge of my healthy habits sooner in life
Too much drinking and too many boyfriends in between ages of 19-24
The business I started that later failed. I’m still paying off the debt. Maybe I won’t regret it so much when the debt is gone.
Not working to my potential in college

Not having more direct conversations with my spouse before we got married about what we ultimately wanted in our lives (i.e., where we wanted to live, how important stability is vs. pursuing our dreams, etc.). He's the greatest, so I'd definitely still marry him if I had it all to do over again. But it would have set the tone from "day one" about how we communicate as a couple and saved us some heartache/conflict down the line.
My biggest regret would be not pursuing a degree in biology because I was told it would not be a lucrative profession.
Caring too much about what other people thought and holding myself back from doing things I would have enjoyed.

As a 17 year old I was on my way trying to become an Olympic athlete in cycling.  My coach was well placed to get me there but I lacked the drive and will to make it happen.  Although I was a champion locally, I failed to get to the next level and looking back on it, I know it was because I chose fun and games (partying) over the sacrifice that was required to get to the Olympics.
That I did not find a partner.  And equally important that I didn't see how being in a partnership could make me a better person.
Not taking more vacations/trips with the kids. Too much time was spent with organized sports activities.
Not being a more present father when my son was younger. Trying to be more of a mentor now that he is in his late 20's.
That I didn't leave an abusive relationship sooner.
Worrying about others opinions of me in high school and throughout my twenties and trying to conform to them
Not spending more time with my parents in their later years, before they died -- which would have meant spending more time with the rest of my family, too, some of whom are also gone now.
not finishing college

The way I treated one of my older sisters. I criticized her often, tattled on her and bossed her around. All around unkind to her. I blamed her for our bad relationship, but as I adult, I saw how I contributed to the problems we had. I apologized about 3 years ago. She and I do not have many things in common, but we are kind to one another. She's one of the most thoughtful people in my life. I can't imagine not having her as my sister.
I wasn’t as empathetic as I could have been towards my now deceased wife
That I didn't encourage my son to play and explore outside more, and learn to practical things.
Not doing more with my children.
I regret getting married young and having a baby instead of finishing college.
I regret never having learned to trust someone unconditionally but to always fear to get hurt.
Drinking too much during college and not focusing enough on developing my talents
I regret not selecting a career that is exciting to me rather than based on practicality and compensation.
Not dancing with my grandmom at an event when I was a kid
I wish I hadn't gotten married so young, and allowed myself to compromise my values for the sake of a man.
I wish I had considered and helped others more. In other words, I regret being too self-centered.
I regret that we did not practice more (nonreligious) traditions with our kids (21, 25). We did do some things routinely - summer lake trips, etc.), but I wish we'd done many more. Sigh.
Not entering a Cher look-alike contest in the 1970s.
Not trying harder to change my career in my mid 30’s to early 40’s.
That I haven't been as involved in my church family as I would like to have been.
That I didn’t take the opportunity to ask people more about their lives.     I read an obituary and learn such interesting things about them that I never knew.

Not saving more when I was a young adult, not being nicer to people when I was a teenager. 

That is 2, sorry
Not taking more chances because I was afraid of looking like a failure

I regret listening to my mother instead of listening to myself regarding pretty much everything - but specifically listening to her regarding my major life decisions... college choice, college major, marriage.
I regret not handling relationship breakups that I initiated more thoughtfully.

The most significant regret I have (though there certainly are others) is how horribly I treated a classmate back in grade school. I'm not sure why we teased her so much. She wasn't a rocket scientist, but she wasn't a bad person. I went along with the crowd, which is not typical of me overall. I'm very ashamed how I gave in to group-think and that this poor girl suffered for it. I should have stood up for her. I often wonder what became of her, and I sincerely hope she rose above the rest of us. She deserves that.
I didn't get into a regular habit of saving more money throughout my life and take better advantage of compound interest.
Not taking a promotion with a better company for less money. Instead I moved to a horribly lead company for more money.
Not having children.
I regret being a verbal bully to my classmates in middle school. As I approach my 40th high school reunion next month I see the long-term, permanent effects of my words and actions.
Not being nicer to my parents.
Not marrying the man I loved because of my family's opinion. He died in a car crash in 1994 when we had just reconnected. To be Loved and Happiness trumps all other endeavours.
I regret not moving my body more: exercising, hiking, dancing, sitting less in general...when I was younger.

Not considering other career choices.  I decided I was going to be a lawyer around 8 years old.  That's what I did.  I had no idea what being a lawyer meant, nor did I consider any alternative possibility.
Choosing the wrong major in college because I listened to what other people told me instead of knowing myself.
Changing my last name when I got married.

I didn't talk to my father more before he passed away.  I could have learned more about our family history, why he opened a business, how dealt with hard times, and made sure I understood his legacy so I could help keep it alive.
I have spent my entire adult life overweight. I feel well and feel active but I am sure it has impacted what people think of me.
Not connecting more with my co-workers
I regret that I was not bolder about love when I was younger, that I held myself back out of fear.
The way I broke up with a long-time girlfriend years ago (25+ years ago)
Not speaking up sooner & louder about the sexual abuse I experienced.
Giving my father a hard time when I was a kid. Only started to have a better relationship with him as a later teenager.
Getting married so young before dating more.
Going straight into work after leaving University and not having too much fun. I have no stories!
I regret not committing to my physical and mental fitness. It means I have way less energy and strength than I could have.
Not studying hard enough
Worrying too much about what other people think of me.
not having child number 2.

Two regrets - one more serious: 

First, I regret having my permanent retainer removed in college and not getting another one. I had braces as a teen and now my lower teeth are crowded again. 

More seriously, I regret not standing up more for myself as a young person in college, in particular, in dating relationships. (#metoo) Some of the resulting baggage has caused difficulty in my marriage.
Spending more time getting involved in my kids' sports engagements.
That I did not learn the power of saving and money management earlier.
Not questioning things and believing everything parents, friends or relatives said

I didn’t go home for Christmas the last year my mother was alive. We had moved back to Europe (after living in the US for three years) in May, and my mother-in-law had commented  how great it would be to have all three of her boys home for  Christmas before the youngest went to Australia for six months. We didn’t think my mother  would die and certainly not so quickly (June the following year), so I said yes. My youngest son never had a Christmas with his maternal grandmother, which is something I regret.
I never put myself out there to play guitar for money
That I didn't dedicate the same level of passion to my family/spouse as I did during my "successful" career.
Not starting my family earlier, I had my first at 37 and haven't been able to have a second.
Not being honest about my sexuality.
That I wasn't more disciplined

Not moving to New York City right after college. No one moves to New York in their 40's...too complicated and expensive once you've lived elsewhere, have kids, etc. It's an experience I will likely never have, and wish I'd seized the opportunity when I was young!
Not having lived abroad for at least a year in my twenties.

I regret marrying (for the first time) at age 20, when I married my high school sweetheart. Although I’ve had a wonderful life, I wish I’d fulfilled more educational and career goals before committing to marriage and family life.

In my early life, there were really only a few professions open to women.  Teaching, Nursing and Social Work. I chose the latter. I don't regret that; I had a fabulous international career which I could not have accomplished without that degree.  But I regret not having more choices.  I'm glad the world has moved on.
Not spending enough time with family
I wish I had maintained my relationship with a sibling despite the estrangement  between him and my mom.
I wish I had spent more time leading a healthier lifestyle - exercise and sleep mainly
Leaving my dad in the hospital, to fly home to my family, when I thought he was on the mend. Bet you can figure out why that is my regret.
That I did not engage in more sports, athletics, and outdoor/nature activities earlier in life.
I wish I had waited longer and dated more people before marrying a second time
Getting into more trouble. Perfectionism is a fickle beast.
I regret not coming out of the closet earlier. All of high school lived in secret.
I wish I had gone to law school. I would have liked a different career.

In 6th grade another girl and I were alternately accepted or outcasts by a particular group of girls. I cannot figure out why I did not just ditch that group and find friends who were friends in deed.
Selling my company too soon.

That I left a private letter on my desk when I was 17, and my Mother read it. It caused a tidal wave of changes in my life and caused my high school boyfriend to be forced into the military during the Viet Nam war.
Not being kind to everyone all the time
Not going to Grand Canyon
I blew my 20's having too much of a good time, took my 30's to get back on track.
I hugely regret having told myself (and therefore believed), that i was a "better mom" to my children BECAUSE I worked full-time.
Taking more time to travel back "home" 2000 miles away to see my parents.
I regret not having the fortitude and foresight to take more risks with my early professional career pathway.
Going to an engineering college when I didn’t have an aptitude for engineering
I regret not understanding and supporting better the struggles my mum went through to raise me and my sister as a single mum.
My biggest regret is letting monetary gains dictate what career I chose, not doing what I wanted to do as a career.
Not being gutsy enough when i was younger in regards to career choices.
I wish I had studied harder and for longer
Not learning a foreign language / studying abroad in college
Cheating on the man who is now my husband
Not allowing myself to experience more joy and happiness.
That I didn't close the doors on my company when the recession began to linger too long.  I ended up losing everything.
Working harder in college and taking advantage of the amazing professors and opportunities there
Not asking my parents enough questions about their lives as children.
Become more involved in broad range of activities in college

I regret not being a better, kinder friend to a girl that went to my high school. Years later I found out that she was being abused by her father during that time and I had done nothing to reach out and become a better friend.
I regret giving up my career to stay at home with my kids
Not having a third baby
That I stopped competing in the last part of my senior year of track
Having had an affair and disrespected my wife.
I never had the chance to tell my son goodbye before he died in an auto accident.
Letting people mess me up, by being too concerned with what others thought.

My behavior around my inlaws.  I treated them like aliens or my opposition.  We could have had a much richer relationship.  This regret has influenced how I treat the men/women my children bring home and marry.  My goal is to be welcoming, kind and forgiving of any missteps they may make.
I would have traveled even more and taken more risks.  Everything is really good, but I wish I had done more.
That I didn’t acknowledge and deal with my depression and anxiety

Not taking a gap year after high school and going on an organised program because at the time I didn’t know anyone going. As an older person who is less afraid and who is friends with the people I would have travelled with it’s a shame I wasn’t braver.
I haven't taken more risks. I played it too safe and followed the rules too much.
I didn’t visit my grandmother more often before she died.
Being present in the moment and participating in all that was offereded versus just hurrying up to "get through all" of it to move to the next step. Be present, breathe, enjoy.

I was in sixth grade, and a bunch of kids were picking on another student. It was joking that just went too far for a couple weeks. I did not participate, but knew it was wrong and never said anything.
Smoking for 20 years
Not remaining in touch with friends who’ve drifted away.
Putting too much focus on business politics instead of standing up for my true values.
Not leaving my marriage when I knew it wasn't salvageable
I allowed my insecurities to hold me back from having and showing my voice at a very young age.

Not buying AAPL (Apple) stock in the 1990s. We were a "bi-coastal" family with Dell and Apple, and I always liked Apple better than Dell. I didn't have a whole buncha money but with "dollar cost averaging" and the stock split bonanza over the years, I would be much better off than I am now.
I wish I had the foresight to learn more about my mother, her life, her choices, her regrets before she died. I was 20.
I regret having married my ex-husband at 21 and then subsequently staying married for 13 years, though my gut always knew the situation was toxic.
I wish I had been kinder and quicker to thank the countless people from family to total strangers who showed me kindnesses of every sort.
Not apologizing when I realized I had hurt someone because I didn't do the right thing when I knew what it was.

I wish that I had spoken out more when I saw or felt something was wrong.  That could have made a difference in how someone felt.  Also, I wish that I had been more empathetic.  Life is hard and we all need encouragement.
Staying safe in a government job I didn’t fit into.

That I stayed in a toxic work environment for a year without actively looking for another job, hoping that the situation would resolve positively. I did eventually leave, but haven't worked in the industry since then.
I wish I hadn't gone to law school. I wish I'd had the courage to pursue my dream of being a novelist instead. I should have gotten my MFA or PhD.
Dating a good friend's girlfriend in high school without telling him.

I regret that I didn't get out of the south for undergraduate and graduate school. I stayed close to the area where I grew up even though my family was gone. Maybe if I had pushed further away from the nest, I'd be different (though I doubt it!)
abortions
not being courageous enough to be a better parent

I had a really wonderful, beautiful, fun girlfriend who became long-distance, and we weren't able to keep it going. She'll always be the one that got away. I'm happily married with three kids now, but I'll always wonder "what if?"
That I masked/covered my anxiety and depression rather than listening to and facing it for most of my life.
Not being more outgoing social positive bold and taking risks in my 20s.
Not speaking up when someone disrespected another person or group because we were in an environment where we should be “civil” ( e.g., work).  I regret not upholding my own values.
An automobile accident which left my younger daughter with a scar on her forehead.  She was only 2, and hasn't seemed bothered by it since, but I still regret it.

I regret not staying on my educational path, right out of high school. I wanted to attend college out of state and become a professional student. I just finished my bachelor's degree two years ago and no longer have a desire to work on my masters.
I regret that I allowed myself to be complacent in work and not be driven more fully.

Not taking the time to enjoy the moment. I wish I had worried less and not let anxiety and stress control the moment. Just with I had taken the time and enjoyed some of the experiences and big moments in my life more.
Not being more gentle with my son as he was growing up.
Not standing up for myself and allowing my parents to push me into studying at university a subject that I wasn’t interested in.
bullying kids in my high school
I wish I had saved more money so I am not catching up now.
Not traveling more - within the US and abroad
Too much focus on work and achievement, which was and still is important, but not enough focus on play - just as important.
I should have had more sex when I was younger...not that I wasn't trying

Military service.
We live in a GREAT Country; we should serve it!
Not realising, prior to getting married, that the man I married and had children with would become an alcoholic.

I regret not pursuing a medical degree instead of education. I felt pressured by my parents to focus on education because it's what they wanted for me, and what they said they would pay for, instead of me pursuing medicine.
Not going in for the kiss with the cute girl I had been hanging out with for a few weeks in college.  Ended up in the friend zone.
That i didn't get into adventure motorcycle riding sooner. And adventuring in a grander way.
Staying in a dead end marriage
Trying too hard to work within the system

Placing too much importance on MY expectations on my kids and not appreciating their amazing, unique qualities. I could have been kinder and given them space to flourish where I now see their self doubt has taken root. I don’t know if I can forgive myself but after recognizing my faults I work to do better every day with them.
I didn't take enough risk.
I wish I had studied music
I regret working too much when my children were young.
Choosing things that I knew I could succeed at as opposed to pushing into an area where failure, or being less successful could be the outcome.
Holding my young stepdaughters at a distance because they had a mom (who I despised- another regret) not acknowledging that they had room in their lives (and hearts) for 2 moms.
I wished I was more of a stand up person, not afraid to speak up or stand out for the greater good and for my own personal life.
That I was not bolder (I am a woman in a male dominated industry) in my youth.
Spending thousands of dollars on training for Stock Options trading.
Not finishing my Boy Scout Eagle Scout requirements
Deciding to have a baby so young
that I did not marry or have a significant other in my life
Getting married too young.
Not taking the opportunity to serve my country.

To have been bolder at a younger age. Not stupid, not crazy, no drugs or alcohol. But things like skydiving, race car driving, volunteering for more dangerous duty while I was in the Navy. That way I’d have more cool things to tell my grandkids about, instead of stories of other people I knew! Ha. Was always kind to people, so no regrets there.
Having sex for the first time with the wrong person.
I regret not practicing the guitar harder, not pushing more to play in a band.
Money planning.  If you start young and continue, you can really have a nice chunk of change set aside.  Managing debt also makes a big difference.
I regret that I did not go to college. I was too scared.
Not having talked more frankly and openly with the love of my life. I let him go on a stupid misunderstanding and regretted it ever since. (I was about 33 years old at the time)

Not taking art classes at school, instead I took Latin and Greek at the insistence of my parents. It is only recently (within the past 5 years) that I have discovered the joy of creating art for myself and I regret all of the missed years.
Asking my wife to marry me and not divorcing when I should have.
Not pursuing my dreams of entering the world of showbiz (as an actor or director) for fear of rejection and failure.
My main regret is joking about other people's feelings and insecurities. I hurt people and, in the end, made myself lonely and unlikeable.
Not being with my father in law when he died
getting married to my ex-wife
I never went to college.
Not leaving bad situations sooner-mainly relationships. Ignoring red flags, only to pay a price later
Spending more time with my mum before she passed away...
Staying too long in an unhappy marriage.
Not stopping work to take care of my mother full time when she was ill.
Not going to grad school when I had the opportunity in my 20s (waited until my 40s to go!)
Caring too much about what other people think/trying to make "them" happy (whoever the hell 'they' are). :P
That I never learned to play a musical instrument.
I wish I had been more attentive to my friends.
